\section{System Model}

We formalize a three-layer architecture consisting of:

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Chai}: an agent orchestration language producing draft outputs and tool actions,
\item \textbf{Alignment Fact Calculator (AFC)}: a semantic sensor layer producing structured alignment evidence,
\item \textbf{Emission Security Policy (ESP)}: a deterministic access control engine governing emission.
\end{itemize}

The execution pipeline is:

\[
\text{Chai} \rightarrow \text{AFC} \rightarrow \text{ESP} \rightarrow \text{Emission}
\]

\subsection{Entities}

An emission attempt is represented as:

\[
\langle s, o, x, C \rangle
\]

where:

\begin{itemize}
\item $s$ is the \textbf{subject} (agent identity),
\item $o$ is the \textbf{object} (emission target),
\item $x$ is the \textbf{draft output},
\item $C$ is the \textbf{execution context} (session metadata, environment, trace).
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Subject and Object Structures}

Subjects are structured records:

\[
s =
\{
\texttt{agent\_id},
\texttt{model},
\texttt{capability},
\texttt{role},
\texttt{trust\_tier}
\}
\]

Objects are structured records:

\[
o =
\{
\texttt{action},
\texttt{channel},
\texttt{destination},
\texttt{audience},
\texttt{persistence}
\}
\]

\subsection{Alignment Fact Calculator (AFC)}

AFC computes a set of structured alignment facts:

\[
F = \text{AFC}(x, s, o, C)
\]

\subsubsection{Evidence Representation}

Each fact is represented as:

\[
\text{Evidence}(T) =
\langle
v, \sigma, m, c, \tau
\rangle
\]

where:

\begin{itemize}
\item $v$ is the measured value,
\item $\sigma$ is the evidence source (local, callee),
\item $m$ is the detection method identifier,
\item $c \in [0,1]$ is the confidence score,
\item $\tau$ is a timestamp.
\end{itemize}

Facts are grouped into typed namespaces:

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{DLP facts:} PII, secrets, credential matches
\item \textbf{Safety facts:} harm category scores
\item \textbf{Schema facts:} structural validation results
\item \textbf{Grounding facts:} citation support metrics
\item \textbf{Tooltrace facts:} attempted external actions
\item \textbf{Risk facts:} aggregated alignment risk indicators
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Streaming Fact Calculation}

For streaming outputs, AFC computes prefix facts:

\[
F_t = \text{AFC}(x_{1:t})
\]

where $x_{1:t}$ denotes the output prefix at time $t$.

AFC maintains bounded internal state for streaming inspection and produces incremental
Fact Bundles.

\subsection{Emission Security Policy (ESP)}

ESP evaluates alignment authorization via the decision function:

\[
d = \text{ESP}(s, o, F)
\]

\subsubsection{Decision Algebra}

Decisions belong to:

\[
D =
\{
\texttt{ALLOW},
\texttt{DENY},
\texttt{REDACT},
\texttt{DEFER},
\texttt{REQUIRE\_HUMAN},
\texttt{DOWNGRADE}
\}
\]

Each decision includes:

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{obligations}: transformation or logging requirements,
\item \textbf{reason codes}: policy justification identifiers,
\item \textbf{trace}: rule evaluation trace.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Policy Representation}

Policies consist of ordered rules:

\[
r_i = \langle effect_i, action_i, predicate_i, obligations_i \rangle
\]

where:

\begin{itemize}
\item $effect_i$ is a decision effect,
\item $action_i$ matches object actions,
\item $predicate_i$ is a boolean expression over $(s, o, F)$,
\item $obligations_i$ defines post-processing requirements.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Evaluation Semantics}

Policy evaluation is defined as:

\begin{enumerate}
\item Rules are evaluated in deterministic order.
\item The first matching rule produces the decision.
\item Deny overrides semantics apply.
\item If no rule matches, the decision is \texttt{DENY}.
\end{enumerate}

ESP evaluation is total and free of external calls.

\subsection{Streaming Enforcement Protocol}

For streaming generation:

\begin{enumerate}
\item Chai produces output prefix $x_{1:t}$.
\item AFC computes prefix facts $F_t$.
\item ESP computes decision $d_t = \text{ESP}(s, o, F_t)$.
\item Runtime executes:
\begin{itemize}
\item emit prefix if $d_t = \texttt{ALLOW}$,
\item buffer prefix if $d_t = \texttt{DEFER}$,
\item transform prefix if $d_t = \texttt{REDACT}$,
\item drop prefix if $d_t = \texttt{DENY}$.
\end{itemize}
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Security Invariants}

The architecture enforces the following invariants:

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Fail-closed emission:} no output is emitted without policy approval.
\item \textbf{Deterministic enforcement:} policy evaluation is deterministic and reproducible.
\item \textbf{Separation of inference and control:} probabilistic fact calculation is separated from deterministic enforcement.
\item \textbf{Auditability:} all emission decisions are traceable to policy rules.
\end{itemize}
